Is there a perference for adding comments in the `else` block of an `if` statement ?

For example:

Case 1:

``` js
// comment about the if block
if (condition) {
  // comment about doStuff()
  doStuff();
} else {  // comment about the else block, what if this is too long ?
  // comment about doOtherStuff();
  doOtherStuff();
}
```

Case 2:

``` js
// comment about the if block
if (condition) {
  // comment about doStuff()
  doStuff();
} else { 
  // comment about the else block

  // comment about doOtherStuff();
  doOtherStuff();
}
```

Case 3:

``` js
// comment about the if block
if (condition) {
  // comment about doStuff()
  doStuff();

  // comment about the else block
} else {
  // comment about doOtherStuff();
  doOtherStuff();
}
```

Not sure if any of these is preferred... is there another way?

The current advice, 

``` text
To convert an array-like object to an array, use Array#slice.

function trigger() {
  var args = Array.prototype.slice.call(arguments);
  ...
}
```

Actually breaks v8's compiling optimizer, just fyi. Any function you do that to can not be optimized. [See the bluebird docs for more info.](https://github.com/petkaantonov/bluebird/wiki/Optimization-killers#3-managing-arguments)

